       &gt;<span class="breadcrumb-link">Dollar Index Gaining Momentum,...</span></span></div>\n<div class="page-title">Bond Market Update</div>\n<div class="story-wrapper">\n<div class="summary-wrapper">\n<div class="summary-box-wrapper">\n<div class="smu-box-title">\n        The market at 00:00 ET</div>\n<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="smu-table">\n<tr>\n<td valign="top"><b>10-Year: </b>....%....\n            <b>GNMAs: </b>....\n            <b>USD/JPY: </b>....\n            <b>EUR/USD: </b></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td height="2"></td>\n</tr>\n</table><br><div class="smu-box-title" style="margin-right:15px;">\n        Moving the Market\n      </div>\n<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="smu-table">\n<tr class="padding5">\n<td class="list-arrow"><img class="arrow-pos" src="/common/images/briefinginvestor/arrowblue.gif"></td>\n<td><p><strong>Wholesale Inventories (10): Briefing 0.7%, consensus 0.7%, prior 0.6%</strong></p>\n<p><strong>Fed will purchase $2.75-3.50B worth of 2017/2018 maturities through POMO</strong></p></td>\n</tr>\n</table>\n</div>\n<div>\n<div class="art-cell-story-title">Dollar Index Gaining Momentum, Tops 76.50</div>\n<div class="u-date">09-Sep-11 07:40 ET  </div>\n<div class="padding-top10 padding-bottom5"><b>10-Yr: </b>-07/32..1.995%..\n        <b>USD/JPY: </b>77.77..\n        <b>EUR/USD: </b>1.3810</div><strong>Momentum</strong>: The dollar index continues to hold the 76.00 level with todayâs strength running it above 76.50.<strong> The recent strength may be a major turning point for the greenback</strong> as some of the major pairs are beginning to work decidedly in its favor. EURUSD is off another 70 pips this morning to 1.3815 as its former 1.40 support is looking more and more distant. The troubles that ail the Eurozone are far from being solved, and this may be the beginning of a much steeper slide for the single currency. French industrial production topped estimates (1.5% MoM actual v. 0.4% MoM expected) to provide a glimmer of good news. GBPUSD continues to battle critical 1.5900/1.5950 support as todayâs 20 pip decline has the pair resting at those levels. If a breakdown does occur, traders will then shift focus to the 1.54 level which is of extreme importance from a technical standpoint. British PPI input fell 1.9% MoM (-1.6% MoM expected) and shows the presence of <strong>deflationary pressures.</strong> USDCHF has reached our .8800 objective in overnight trade and is now contending with its 200-day moving average. Momentum has shifted in the dollarâs favor, but it would not be surprising to see some giveback as the 200-day may prove problematic. <br />\n<br />\nUSDJPY is higher by 30 pips at 77.80 as it has finally pushed through 77.50 resistance. The pairâs 50-day moving average is applying overhead pressure and a breakout will likely lead to a flirtation with the 79.00 level. Japanâs final GDP for the second quarter met -0.5% QoQ expectations. AUDUSD is lower by 60 pips at 1.0520 and will now look to hold 1.05 support. Should that level give way the 1.04 area will be important as the 200-day lurks in the vicinity. Chinese data was plentiful as inflation readings painted a mixed picture with CPI easing to 6.2% YoY (6.3% YoY expected) and PPI falling to 7.3% YoY (7.2% YoY expected). Other data out in the middle kingdom showed fixed asset investment fall to 25.0% YTD/Y, industrial production decline to 13.5% YoY, and retail sales in-line at 17.0% YoY. The Chinese renminbi weakened to 6.3887.<br />\n<br />\nUSDCAD has tacked on another 30 pips and has pushed back through the .9900 level. A thrust through .9950 will be very kind to the pair and will likely lead to a breakout. USDCAD has not seen a close above parity since January 31. The move comes after<strong> a weak jobs reading in Canada</strong> which showed employment fell 5.5K (24.2K expected) and the unemployment rate ticked up to 7.3%. Housing starts are due out later this morning.<br />\nÂ <br />\