13e8192115d5">0</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="bar-left article-actions">\r\n\t<div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style ">\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_email it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1"> Email</a>\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_print it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1"> Print</a>\r\n\t<a href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pubid=fxstreet" class="addthis_button_compact it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1">Share</a>\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_tweet it-sharethis-button" tw:width="90" tw:via="FXstreetNews" tw:related="FXstreetUpdate"></a>\r\n\t<span class="ib btn-plusone" ><a class="addthis_button_google_plusone it-sharethis-button"  rel="nofollow" g:plusone:size="medium" g:plusone:width="70" ></a></span>\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_facebook_like it-sharethis-button" fb:like:layout="button_count" fb:like:action="recommend" fb:like:show_faces="false" fb:like:width="130" > </a>\r\n\t<a href="/technical/forex-signals/indices-and-oil-strategies/index.xml" class=" btn-social-s1"><b class="i-rss2 icon" title="Subscribe to this report">RSS</b></a>\r\n\t</div>\r\n</div><!--bar-left.article-actions-->\r\n\r\n</div><!--article-utilities-->\r\n\r\n</div><!--article-header-->\r\n\r\n<div class="article-content">\r\n    \r\n<div class="article-aside">\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="article-text">\r\n<h3>S&amp;P 500 (Sep 11) INTRADAY</h3><a onclick="FXStreet.openwin(this.href, '_blank', 1025, 446, 1, 0, 0, 0);return false;" href="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/Reports/fb47c1c2-125e-43c4-890b-47d897d9a476/eur_20110909122347.jpg"><img width="300" height="128" title="S &amp; P" alt="S &amp; P" src="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/Reports/fb47c1c2-125e-43c4-890b-47d897d9a476/eur_20110909122347.jpg" /></a><br />\n<p> <strong>Review</strong> It was a mixed session for the majority of yesterday before a general move lower in the latter stages. In the morning the E-mini S&amp;P traded up to test Wednesdayâs high at 1202.25 where solid resistance was found. During the press conference at 13.30BST ECBâs Trichet returned to a neutral stance on monetary policy as expected while saying that the risks to Eurozone growth were no longer broadly balanced but now skewed to the downside. This comment pushed equities lower with support being found at the US cash open as investors began positioning themselves ahead of Obamaâs jobs speech. However, having pushed to make another test of the dayâs highs, stocks edged back towards the lows as Bernanke stopped short of signalling any monetary policy changes in a speech that provided little new information from the Jackson Hole Symposium.</p>\n<p> <strong>Strategy</strong> Overnight Obama announced a $447 billion jobs plan which is bigger than the $300 billion expected. It is highly unlikely that all the measures will pass but the payroll tax cut which makes up over half the package could win bipartisan support. However, the lack of initial positive reaction is due to the jobs package's route into actual legislation is likely to be slowed by political wrangling and also $447bln is effectively being removed from the fiscal adjustment efforts that were already considered to be underweight. We have just tested the overnight Obama low at 1178.25 and with the main events of the week over it is likely that the Eurozone concerns will weigh on risk assets today ahead of this weekendâs G7 summit. We have a short entry at the pivot at 1190.75 for this afternoon.</p>\n<p> <strong>Alternative Scenario </strong>Positive news from Greece regarding their private bond holder participation may lift equities and a break of R1 resistance at 1199.50 will lead to a test of yesterdayâs high at 1203.75</p>\n<p><br /></p>\n<h3> EUR/USD INTRADAY</h3><a onclick="FXStreet.openwin(this.href, '_blank', 1020, 487, 1, 0, 0, 0);return false;" href="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/Reports/fb47c1c2-125e-43c4-890b-47d897d9a476/EURUSD_20110909122714.jpg"><img width="300" height="141" title="EURUSD" alt="EURUSD" src="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/Reports/fb47c1c2-125e-43c4-890b-47d897d9a476/EURUSD_20110909122714.jpg" /></a><br />\n<p> <strong>Review </strong>The EURUSD lost further ground and closed firmly below the $1.40 handle yesterday as ECBâs Trichet put on hold the recent rate hiking cycle citing that downside risks to economic growth have intensified. The statements from JCT was fairly non-committal to future monetary policy expectations but the flat stance and comments that growth risks were no longer broadly balanced weighed on the euro. The currency pair took another leg lower to finish down 1.29% for the session as Bernanke reiterated comments from his Jackson Hole speech and refrained from signalling any further action.</p>\n<p> <strong>Strategy </strong>This morning the Euro has made a new six month low against the US dollar breaking through key support at 1.3837 which was the July 2011 low. We have been bearish on the Euro over the last two weeks and the move this morning confirms our medium term bearish target of 1.3428 which was the February 2011 low. We are bearish because the Eurozone crisis is still a huge concern, the Eurozone economic growth has slowed and in our view is now under performing and in our mind the ECB are now more likely to cut interest rates rather than raise them. We have a short strategy again for this afternoon looking for the July low to provide strong resistance at 1.3837.</p>\n<p> <strong>Alternative Scenario</strong> Positive news from Greece regarding the private bond holder bond swap may give the Euro some brief respite and a break above yesterdayâs low at 1.3873 may lead to a test of the overnight high at 1.3937</p>\n<p><br /></p>\n<h3> US 10Y T-Note (Dec 11) INTRADAY</h3><a onclick="FXStreet.openwin(this.href, '_blank', 1025, 461, 1, 0, 0, 0);return false;" href="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/Reports/fb47c1c2-125e-43c4-890b-47d897d9a476/US_20110909122852.jpg"><img width="300" height="133" title="US 10Y T-Note" alt="US 10Y T-Note" src="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/Reports/fb47c1c2-125e-43c4-890b-47d897d9a476/US_20110909122852.jpg" /></a><br />\n<p> <strong>Review </strong>The main event yesterday came in the form of a disillusioned central banker who for once realised that perhaps inflation may not be the primary concern but still remained stubborn against monetary easing. However, traders understand the procedure and the ECB cannot go from hawkish to dovish in one fail swoop (that would mean they would admit to being wrong), so this intermediate stage allows them to be more dovish in the next meeting. The first reaction to this statement was for a move out of risk and T-Notes hit our entry short at 130.105 just before the statement and then moved to our target one, 130.005 by 15:30 BST. We then hit the entry short again at 19:30, which is where the market closed.</p>\n<p> <strong>Strategy </strong>Yesterday we saw a sideways ranging market with our resistance level 130.105 capping the upside. This level has already come into play twice this morning highlighting the relevance of this analysis. Given this morningâs return to pessimism surrounding Greece and due to the fact that the major events this week are out the way we feel risk may move out of the markets heading into the weekend. Therefore we will look to enter long at yesterdayâs low 129.295. A more aggressive trader may chose an entry on the trend support higher seen since yesterday as shown below.</p>\n<p> <strong>Alternative Scenario</strong> A return to positive sentiment after Obamaâs job reform proposal last night could see T-Notes break the trend higher this week to test Wednesdayâs low of 129.230.</p>\n<p><br /></p>\n<h3> Crude Oil (Oct 11) INTRADAY</h3><a onclick="FXStreet.openwin(this.href, '_blank', 1008, 492, 1, 0, 0, 0);return false;" href="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/Reports/fb47c1c2-125e-43c4-890b-47d897d9a476/Crude_20110909122929.jpg"><img width="300" height="144" title="Crude Oil" alt="Crude Oil" src="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/Reports/fb47c1c2-125e-43c4-890b-47d897d9a476/Crude_20110909122929.jpg" /></a><br />\n<p> <strong>Review</strong> WTI Crude had a tight range bound session yesterday repeatedly finding support at the pivot level of $88.60 and with the upside being capped by Wednesdayâs high at $99.30. The market was consolidating the gains from the previous two sessions as a confluence of factors continue to influence direction. Trichet, Bernanke and Obama all failed ultimately to generate the risk appetite that investors craved and risk assets ultimately sold off. But the oil price remained supported by the threat of major weather systems forming in the Gulf of Mexico. This lead to crude prices remaining relatively unmoved and closing at $89.05.</p>\n<p> <strong>Strategy </strong>Crude prices have drifted lower this morning along with other risk assets. On the face of it Obamaâs jobs package announced last night seems to be a positive step for economic growth. He proposed a $447bln package of tax cuts and infrastructure projects but the reality is that by the time the politicians have argued and wrangled the final legislation may look completely different. So a distinct feeling of dis-satisfaction has mildly weighed on crude prices this morning and in the absence of any key news flow today we expect this gentle trend lower to continue. We have a short entry for this afternoon at the pivot level at $89.26.</p>\n<p> <strong>Alternative Scenario</strong> If there a re significant developments with regard to the weather system forming in the Gulf of Mexico then this can drive crude prices higher and a break above Wednesdayâs high at $90.30 may lead to a test of R2 at $90.99.</p><ul class="files">\n\t<li><img src="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/FileIcon.aspx?mime=application/pdf&amp;amp;width=16" alt="Download Full Indices And Oil Strategies" title="Download Full Indices And Oil Strategies" />&nbsp;<a href="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/Reports/fb47c1c2-125e-43c4-890b-47d897d9a476/a069e6d0-2b27-4b34-8213-1b3087e3f89d.pdf">Download Full Indices And Oil Strategies</a></li>\n</ul><div class="entryfooter">\n\t\n</div>\t\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="section p10">\r\n<a class="addthis_button_facebook_like it-sharethis-button" fb:like:layout="standard" fb:like:action="recommend" fb:like:show_faces="false" fb:like:width="450" fb:like:height="33" > </a>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="article-footer layout-bar">\r\n\t<div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style">\r\n\t<div class="bar-left ">\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_email it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1"> Email</a>\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_print it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1"> Print</a>\r\n\t<a href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pubid=fxstreet" class="addthis_button_compact it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1">Share</a>\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_tweet it-sharethis-button" tw:width="90" tw:via="FXstreetNews" tw:related="FXstreetUpdate"></a>\r\n\t<span class="ib btn-plusone" ><a class="addthis_button_google_plusone it-sharethis-button"  rel="nofollow" g:plusone:size="medium" g:plusone:width="70" ></a></span>\r\n\t</div>\r\n\r\n\t<p class="permalink bar-right">\r\n\t<span class="datetime">\r\n\tPublished On \r\n\t<a href="http://www.fxstreet.com/technical/forex-signals/indices-and-oil-strategies/2011/09/09/" title="http://www.fxstreet.com/technical/forex-signals/indices-and-oil-strategies/2011/09/09/">\r\n\tFri, Sep 9 2011, 12:35 GMT</a></span></p>\r\n\t</div>\r\n</div><!--article-footer.layout-bar-->\r\n\r\n</div><!--.section-article.article-report-->\r\n\r\n<div class="section-footer section">\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class="grid6 main-info"> \r\n\t<h2>About this Report</h2>\r\n\t<p><a href="http://www.amplifytrading.com/"><img src="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/images/-provider-logo2-en.jpeg" alt="Amplify Trading"/></a></p>\r\n\t<p>Amplify Trading</p>\r\n\t<p><a href="http://www.amplifytrading.com/">http://