ities layout-bar">\r\n<div class="bar-left article-vote">\r\n<span>Vote:</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><a src="http://cdn.fxstreet.com/images/voteup.png" class="i-vote-up icon vote" name="7ab9cdcf-9a30-4f55-9521-ec34208e1e28">Vote up:</a><span class="up7ab9cdcf-9a30-4f55-9521-ec34208e1e28">2</span></li>\r\n\t<li><a src="http://cdn.fxstreet.com/images/votedown.png" class="i-vote-down icon vote" name="7ab9cdcf-9a30-4f55-9521-ec34208e1e28">Vote down:</a><span class="down7ab9cdcf-9a30-4f55-9521-ec34208e1e28">0</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="bar-left article-actions">\r\n\t<div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style ">\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_email it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1"> Email</a>\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_print it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1"> Print</a>\r\n\t<a href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pubid=fxstreet" class="addthis_button_compact it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1">Share</a>\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_tweet it-sharethis-button" tw:width="90" tw:via="FXstreetNews" tw:related="FXstreetUpdate"></a>\r\n\t<span class="ib btn-plusone" ><a class="addthis_button_google_plusone it-sharethis-button"  rel="nofollow" g:plusone:size="medium" g:plusone:width="70" ></a></span>\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_facebook_like it-sharethis-button" fb:like:layout="button_count" fb:like:action="recommend" fb:like:show_faces="false" fb:like:width="130" > </a>\r\n\t<a href="/fundamental/market-view/morning-report/index.xml" class=" btn-social-s1"><b class="i-rss2 icon" title="Subscribe to this report">RSS</b></a>\r\n\t</div>\r\n</div><!--bar-left.article-actions-->\r\n\r\n</div><!--article-utilities-->\r\n\r\n</div><!--article-header-->\r\n\r\n<div class="article-content">\r\n    \r\n<div class="article-aside">\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="article-text">\r\n<h3>Market wrap</h3>\n<p> <strong>Markets remain decidedly risk averse.</strong> Neither Chairman Bernanke nor President Trichet instilled much confidence today sending equities lower and the USD higher. Trichet sounded more dovish at the ECBâs monthly press conference - the ECB cut their growth and inflation forecasts and they moderated their assessment of medium term infl ation risks. The ECB has entered an extended pause. But, the tone of Trichetâs last press conference was somber, even combative at times and did little to assuage concerns about the EU debt crisis. That, and the more dovish tone saw EUR/USD fall sharply overnight, from around 1.4050 to lows of 1.3950 in NY AM trade. Bernankeâs speech later in the day prompted another leg lower sending EUR to session lows of 1.3876. Key long term technical supports for EUR have given way today - bullish trendline support going back to June 2010 and the 200 day moving average were both pierced. EUR fell against all the G10 currencies with the obvious exception of CHF.</p>\n<p> <strong>AUD </strong>and <strong>NZD </strong>were solid out-performers in European trading and through a good part of the EUR carnage but gave back their gains as the day wore on. From post-employment lows beneath 1.06 <strong>AUD </strong>ground back to 1.0660 by mid-morning NY. <strong>NZD </strong>rose from around 0.8320 to 0.8380. However, as Benankeâs speech commenced <strong>EURâs </strong>sell off accelerated and both <strong>AUD </strong>and <strong>NZD </strong>relinquished their gains. Bernankeâs speech was mostly a rehash of his Jackson Hole speech. He off ered no specifi c fresh clues for the all important 20-21 Sep FOMC meeting. Bernanke noted the Fed retains a range of tools and that the FOMC will evaluate its options at their next meeting. The lack of specifi cs weighed on sentiment. BY NY afternoon trade the <strong>AUD </strong>was chopping below 1.06 while the <strong>NZD </strong>was back near 0.8320.</p>\n<p> <strong>The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 85pts (-0.7%) overnight,</strong> gold rose $41/oz while copper was fi rmer (oddly), rising 0.6%. On the data front the US trade defi cit narrowed almost $7bn to $44.8bn in July while US initial jobless claims rose 2k to 414k in the week ending Sep 3. The pace at which fi rms are laying off workers seems fairly constant of late. German exports were down 1.8% in July. That is the third month in four that export values have fallen, and annual growth has slowed from 21.6% yr in Jan to just 6.9% yr six months later. The result contrasts with surging industrial production (up 4% in July) although foreign orders for German factory output have softened lately.</p>\n<p><br /></p>\n<h3> Economic wrap</h3>\n<p> <strong>The US Fed chairman Bernanke in Minnesota.</strong> More hints about what is on the table at the Sept 20-21 FOMC meeting? He speaks at 1730GMT. <strong>US trade deficit narrowed almost $7bn to $44.8bn in July.</strong> Exports jumped 3.6%, with capital goods, industrial supplies and autos notably strong, while imports slipped 0.2%,despite a 15% surge in autos. Lower oil import prices and volumes were a factor (as clearly was the resumption of auto trade with part supply problems being resolved). As with many data series, July was a favoured month for the trade report, but there are some one-off s in there that wonât be sustained. US initial jobless claims rose 2k to 414k in w/e Sep 3, so the pace at which firms are laying off workers seems fairly constant; there was no Hurricane Irene impact in there.</p>\n<p> <strong>Canadian trade deficit C$0.8bn in July,</strong> the lowest deficit in four months. Exports rose 2.2% lifted by autos, industrial, machinery and agriculture; imports rose 0.5% with energy and auto gains partially off set by a decline in the machinery/industrial sectors. In July, building permits rose 6.3% by value with the residential component boosted by a 30% jump in multiples; single family house permits rose 3.4%. Non-residential permits fell 4.5%. Meanwhile, new house prices rose 0.1% in July, their softest gain in four months.</p>\n<p> <strong>European Central Bank drops tightening bias.</strong> The statement following the on hold rate decision noted that âWe will continue to monitor very closely all developmentsâ but â...with respect to upside risks to price stabilityâ (which has been there most of this year) was dropped. Now, the ECB Council âviews the risks to the medium-term outlook for price developments as being broadly balancedâ. Furthermore, whereas in August, the risks to the economic outlook for the euro area âremain broadly balanced in an environment of particularly high uncertaintyâ, they are now assessed as âon the downsideâ. Revised staff forecast ranges were published, with lower central points for GDP in 2011 (1.6% vs 1.9% in June) and 2012 (1.3% vs 1.7%), although the inflation forecasts were little changed (2.6% and 1.7% respectively).</p>\n<p> <strong>German exports down 1.8% in July.</strong> That is the third month in four that export values have fallen, and annual growth has slowed from 21.6% yr in Jan to just 6.9% yr six months later. The result contrasts with surging industrial production (up 4% in July) although foreign orders for German factory output have softened lately.</p>\n<p> <strong>Bank of England on hold at 0.5%</strong> and asset purchases maintained at Â£200bn. No detailed statement was issued, as is normal when policy is unchanged.</p>\n<p><br /></p>\n<h3> Market outlook</h3>\n<p> <strong>AUD/USD and NZD/USD outlook next 24 hours: </strong>AUD and NZD should be commended for their stoicism but the broader atmospherics remain decidedly risk averse. EUR has broken important long term support levels as well. Sellers are likely to cap both AUD and NZD on strength. A short term double top in AUD is in place at 1.0660 while NZD will struggle into 0.8400.</p><ul class="files">\n\t<li><img src="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/FileIcon.aspx?mime=application/pdf&amp;amp;width=16" alt="Download Full Morning Report" title="Download Full Morning Report" />&nbsp;<a href="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/Reports/4917805e-be19-481e-9baa-eb355040e9cb/b1e1365a-229a-43db-bd00-d0e2baf5fae7.pdf">Download Full Morning Report</a></li>\n</ul><div class="entryfooter">\n\t\n</div>\t\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="section p10">\r\n<a class="addthis_button_facebook_like it-sharethis-button" fb:like:layout="standard" fb:like:action="recommend" fb:like:show_faces="false" fb:like:width="450" fb:like:height="33" > </a>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="article-footer layout-bar">\r\n\t<div class="addthis_toolbox addthis_default_style">\r\n\t<div class="bar-left ">\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_email it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1"> Email</a>\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_print it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1"> Print</a>\r\n\t<a href="http://www.addthis.com/bookmark.php?v=250&amp;pubid=fxstreet" class="addthis_button_compact it-sharethis-button btn-social-s1">Share</a>\r\n\t<a class="addthis_button_tweet it-sharethis-button" tw:width="90" tw:via="FXstreetNews" tw:related="FXstreetUpdate"></a>\r\n\t<span class="ib btn-plusone" ><a class="addthis_button_google_plusone it-sharethis-button"  rel="nofollow" g:plusone:size="medium" g:plusone:width="70" ></a></span>\r\n\t</div>\r\n\r\n\t<p class="permalink bar-right">\r\n\t<span class="datetime">\r\n\tPublished On \r\n\t<a href="http://www.fxstreet.com/fundamental/market-view/morning-report/2011/09/09/" title="http://www.fxstreet.com/fundamental/market-view/morning-report/2011/09/09/">\r\n\tFri, Sep 9 2011, 05:41 GMT</a></span></p>\r\n\t</div>\r\n</div><!--article-footer.layout-bar-->\r\n\r\n</div><!--.section-article.article-report-->\r\n\r\n<div class="section-footer section">\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class="grid6 main-info"> \r\n\t<h2>About this Report</h2>\r\n\t<p><a href="http://www.westpac.co.nz"><img src="http://mediaserver.fxstreet.com/images/westpac-institutional-bank-provider-logo-en.gif" alt="Westpac Institutional Bank"/></a></p>\r\n\t<p>Westpac Institutional Bank</p>\r\n\t<p><a href="http://www.westpac.co.n